Use a hash map for O(n) time and O(n) space, instead of the naive O(n²) brute force.

```go
func twoSum(nums []int, target int) (int, int) {
	seen := make(map[int]int, len(nums))
	for i, v := range nums {
		if j, ok := seen[target-v]; ok {
			return j, i
		}
		seen[v] = i
	}
	return -1, -1
}
```

Algorithm rationale:
- A map lookup is O(1) average, so a single pass suffices.
- We store `value → index` as we scan; for each element we check if its complement already exists.
- Worst-case time: O(n). Worst-case space: O(n).
- The brute-force nested loop is O(n²) time and should be avoided for large inputs.
- If the slice were sorted, binary search per element gives O(n log n) time and O(1) space — a viable alternative when allocations are costly.

**Design**

Use the token bucket algorithm: each bucket refills at `rate` tokens/sec, capped at `burst`.

```go
package ratelimit

import (
	"sync"
	"time"
)

type bucket struct {
	tokens    float64
	last      time.Time
	rate      float64 // tokens per second
	burst     float64
}

func (b *bucket) allow(now time.Time) bool {
	elapsed := now.Sub(b.last).Seconds()
	b.last = now
	b.tokens = min(b.burst, b.tokens+elapsed*b.rate)
	if b.tokens >= 1 {
		b.tokens--
		return true
	}
	return false
}

type Limiter struct {
	mu      sync.Mutex
	buckets map[string]*bucket
	rate    float64
	burst   float64
}

func New(rate, burst float64) *Limiter {
	return &Limiter{
		buckets: make(map[string]*bucket),
		rate:    rate,
		burst:   burst,
	}
}

func (l *Limiter) Allow(userID string) bool {
	now := time.Now()
	l.mu.Lock()
	b, ok := l.buckets[userID]
	if !ok {
		b = &bucket{tokens: l.burst, last: now, rate: l.rate, burst: l.burst}
		l.buckets[userID] = b
	}
	ok = b.allow(now)
	l.mu.Unlock()
	return ok
}
```

**Design decisions:**
- Single `sync.Mutex` is sufficient for moderate concurrency; for very high contention shard the map by hash.
- Store `float64` tokens to accumulate fractional tokens correctly.
- Memory: one bucket per active user; add a periodic cleanup goroutine that evicts buckets idle > TTL to avoid unbounded growth.
- Alternative: `golang.org/x/time/rate` per user stored in a `sync.Map` with eviction — same concept, battle-tested implementation.

**Complexity**
- Time: O(n log n) in all cases (best, average, worst).
- Space: O(n) auxiliary for the temporary merge buffer (plus O(log n) call stack).

```go
func mergeSort(s []int) []int {
	if len(s) <= 1 {
		return s
	}
	mid := len(s) / 2
	left := mergeSort(s[:mid])
	right := mergeSort(s[mid:])
	return merge(left, right)
}

func merge(a, b []int) []int {
	out := make([]int, 0, len(a)+len(b))
	i, j := 0, 0
	for i < len(a) && j < len(b) {
		if a[i] <= b[j] {
			out = append(out, a[i])
			i++
		} else {
			out = append(out, b[j])
			j++
		}
	}
	out = append(out, a[i:]...)
	out = append(out, b[j:]...)
	return out
}
```

**Recursion explanation:**
- Divide: split the slice in half until each sub-slice has ≤1 element (trivially sorted).
- Conquer: merge pairs of sorted sub-slices bottom-up.
- Recurrence: T(n) = 2T(n/2) + O(n). By the Master Theorem (case 2), T(n) = O(n log n).

**When to prefer over quicksort:** merge sort is stable and guarantees O(n log n) worst case. Use quicksort (or Go's `sort.Slice` which uses pdqsort) for in-place sorting when stability isn't needed.

```go
package stack

type Stack[T any] struct {
	data []T
}

func (s *Stack[T]) Push(v T) {
	s.data = append(s.data, v)
}

func (s *Stack[T]) Pop() (T, bool) {
	if len(s.data) == 0 {
		var zero T
		return zero, false
	}
	n := len(s.data) - 1
	v := s.data[n]
	s.data[n] = *new(T) // clear reference to avoid memory leak for pointer types
	s.data = s.data[:n]
	return v, true
}

func (s *Stack[T]) Peek() (T, bool) {
	if len(s.data) == 0 {
		var zero T
		return zero, false
	}
	return s.data[len(s.data)-1], true
}

func (s *Stack[T]) Len() int { return len(s.data) }
```

**Design notes:**
- `[T any]` means T can be any type; use `[T comparable]` or a custom constraint if operations on T are needed.
- The `*new(T)` trick writes the zero value to the slot before shrinking the slice, preventing the GC from retaining a pointer through the underlying array.
- Backed by a slice for amortised O(1) push and O(1) pop — superior cache performance over a linked-list stack.
- Not goroutine-safe by design; wrap with a mutex if shared access is needed.

