**Goroutine leak**
A goroutine leak occurs when a goroutine is started but never terminates — it blocks forever waiting on a channel, lock, or I/O that will never complete. Over time, leaked goroutines accumulate, consuming memory and OS scheduler resources.

**Common causes**
```go
// 1. Channel send with no receiver
func leak() {
	ch := make(chan int)
	go func() { ch <- 42 }() // blocked forever if no one reads
}

// 2. Missing context cancellation
func fetchForever(ctx context.Context) {
	go func() {
		for {
			// forgot to check ctx.Done()
			time.Sleep(time.Second)
		}
	}()
}
```

**Detection**
```bash
# Runtime goroutine count
runtime.NumGoroutine()

# pprof goroutine profile
curl http://localhost:6060/debug/pprof/goroutine?debug=2

# goleak in tests (github.com/uber-go/goleak)
func TestFoo(t *testing.T) {
	defer goleak.VerifyNone(t)
	// ... test code
}
```

